{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490894"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:21:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:21:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"775"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/775"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.05,0.17,0.36,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52658"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/775"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38021"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"1158"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8147"},{"type":"tags","id":"8237"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15351"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52658"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a palpable lump in her left breast. She noticed reddish marks of nipple discharge on her brassiere today. Her last mammogram was performed two years ago with normal results. She is concerned about breast cancer, as her mother was diagnosed with triple-negative breast cancer at age 72.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A firm, non-tender mass is palpable in the upper inner quadrant of the left breast and there is bilateral nipple retraction. On leaning forward, dimpling of the breast is seen on the left side. The mass does not move when she adducts her arms. The skin over the left breast has an orange peel appearance (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following physical findings is most useful in staging disease in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Appearance of the overlying skin","Bloody nipple discharge","Tethering of the skin","Fixity to pectoral muscles","Nipple retraction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most useful physical finding for staging in this patient is the \u003Cstrong\u003Eappearance of the overlying skin\u003C/strong\u003E. The stem describes an \u0027orange peel appearance\u0027 of the skin over the left breast, which is known as peau d\u0027orange. This finding is indicative of dermal lymphatic obstruction and is often associated with inflammatory breast cancer or advanced breast cancer. In the TNM staging system for breast cancer, skin involvement such as peau d\u0027orange suggests a T4b stage, which includes skin oedema, ulceration, or ipsilateral satellite skin nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBloody nipple discharge\u003C/strong\u003E is a concerning symptom that may indicate breast cancer, particularly when unilateral and spontaneous. However, it does not directly affect TNM staging. While it prompts further investigation, it is not a direct factor in determining the stage of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETethering of the skin\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as skin retraction or dimpling, can occur due to contraction of fibrous tissue within the breast associated with underlying cancer. This dimpling is caused by traction of the tumour on Cooper\u0027s ligaments. However, it is not directly incorporated into the TNM staging system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFixity to the pectoral muscles\u003C/strong\u003E, as indicated by restriction of mobility of the lump on adduction, does not affect T staging. It is the involvement of the chest wall (ribs and intercostal muscles) that qualifies as T4a stage of the primary tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENipple retraction\u003C/strong\u003E or inversion is a clinical sign where the nipple appears pulled inwards. Bilateral nipple retraction is more likely associated with benign breast disease like fibrocystic disease. Unilateral nipple retraction can be a sign of breast cancer, particularly when associated with a palpable lump and blood-stained nipple discharge. However, it alone does not directly affect TNM staging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, while all these findings are important clinical signs that warrant further investigation, the appearance of the overlying skin, specifically peau d\u0027orange, is most directly relevant to staging breast cancer according to the TNM system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["T4 staging of breast cancer signifies direct extension of the tumour into the chest wall (ribs and intercostal muscles), or overlying skin with ulceration or macroscopic nodules, or oedema (including peau d\u0027orange) indicative of advanced disease."],"references":["Gaillard F, Rasuli B, Bell D, et al. Breast cancer (staging). In: Radiopaedia.org [online]. 2020. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/breast-cancer-staging-1","Koh J, Kim MJ. Introduction of a New Staging System of Breast Cancer for Radiologists: An Emphasis on the Prognostic Stage. Korean J Radiol. 2019 Jan;20(1):69-82. doi: 10.3348/kjr.2018.0231. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6315072/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38021"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"775"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20569"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20569"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/yfw0Oo0iQ8upebUDZ0xWjqkc169mvH.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/yfw0Oo0iQ8upebUDZ0xWjqkc169mvH.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38021"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-08T20:35:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-08T20:36:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"775"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52658"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"posi